    "John T. Carroll": "). This coupling of the participle parakal\u014dn (exhorting,\nencouraging) and the verb euangelizeto (he was declaring good news) recalls\nv. 18),\nit becomes clear that the reduction in the women\u2019s audience from the Eleven-\nwith-others (\nv. 18). This\ncharacter does not know who is speaking to him and will soon show himself\nto lack understanding more comprehensively, yet addresses Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` as if only he,\nassumed to be an outsider staying (paroikeis) in Jerusalem, lacks knowledge of\nthe topic under discussion. The entire scene, though, builds toward the disclosure\nof understanding that only Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, the \u201cuninformed stranger,\u201d can provide.10\nWhen Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, to all appearances playing the part of uninformed outsider, asks\nthe two disciples what sorts of things Cleopas is referring to (\nv. 19a), \u201cthey\u201d\nrespond with a detailed recital of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 prophetic ministry, its violent end in\nJerusalem, and its mysterious aftermath. The one they were convinced was\nthe sign-attested prophet sent by God (\n18. On the omission of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 greeting in some Western textual witnesses, see translation\nnote a. This wish for \u201ccommunal well-being\u201d (Green 854) is, however, congruent with one of the\ncentral motifs of the Lukan narrative (e.g., 1:79; 2:14, 29; 7:50; 8:48; 10:5\u20136; 19:38; but note also\n12:51; 19:42).\nThe Resurrection of the Messiah\n491\nor antiseparationist concerns), follows Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 words with a narrator\u2019s notice\nthat he proceeds to provide this tangible demonstration: \u201cHe showed them his\nhands and feet\u201d\u2014presumably bearing the wounds inflicted during crucifixion,\nalthough this is not stated.19 Without the verse, the full force of legitimating\n\u201cproof\u201d rests on the authoritative word of the risen Lord, including his invitation\n[v_Luk_24_40] to \u201ctouch me and see\u201d (Luke 24:40).\nThe point being scored is twofold and emphatically pressed: the full (albeit\nresurrected) embodiment of the living Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, and therefore assurance of the\ncontinuity of person, self, and identity between the risen one and the Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` of\nthe ministry (and cross): \u201cIt\u2019s me!\u201d To the extent that Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` appears here as\n[v_Luk_14_14] an exemplar of the resurrection life (cf. Luke 14:14; 20:34\u201338),20 life in the\nfuture realm of God, commencing already in the \u201ctoday\u201d of the penitent crimi-\nnal\u2019s Paradise (23:43), is a resurrection life that, while free of at least some\nprior constraints of time, space, and movement, is embodied. As such, it is an\nexistence that continues the life, self, and identity that preceded death. This\nis no disembodied spirit, for as Luke\u2019s audience knows, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` has committed\nhis spirit to God with his dying breath (23:46), only in resurrection to receive\nhis body back, no longer susceptible to corrupting decay\u2014as the apostolic\n[v_Psa_16_10] kerygma will put it in Acts (2:27, 31; 13:34\u201337, drawing from Ps 16:10 [15:10\nlxx, diaphthora, corruption]).\nIn this appearance of the risen Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` to the whole band of disciples, the pat-\ntern of resistance to faith overcome only by Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 presence and interpreting\nword is repeated once more. Not even the sight of him and the hearing of his\nassurance, \u201cSee, .\u00a0.\u00a0. it\u2019s me!\u201d (24:39), is sufficient to elicit faith. The gathered\ncompany react with joy, to be sure, but it is an exuberance still wedded to dis-\ntrust of what their eyes and ears are disclosing to them (\nv. 41a). The reality they\nare encountering is \u201ctoo good to be true\u201d (Green 855), and so, just as in",
