    "John T. Carroll": "), phrasing that\nrecalls Gabriel\u2019s announcement to Mary `[char_Mary_Ref]` concerning Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 paternity (1:34\u201335)\nand Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 youthful awareness that God is his father (2:49). In the public view,\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` is Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`\u2019s son (e.g., 2:48, 51; 4:22), and by welcoming Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` into his\nhousehold, Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` has taken him into his family line; nevertheless, readers\nhave received deeper insight: he is uniquely God\u2019s Son. The conclusion of the\ngenealogy clinches the point, for Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 family line originates in God. Mention\nof Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` as progenitor, however, also connects Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` to the history and fortunes\n[v_Luk_3_6] of all humanity (cf. \u201call flesh,\u201d Luke 3:6).\nSandwiched between the baptismal confirmation of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 identity as\nbeloved Son of God (3:22) and the testing in the wilderness, which probes the\nmeaning of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 divine sonship and its implications for life and vocation (\u201cIf\nindeed you are the Son of God\u201d: 4:3, 9), the genealogy accents Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 identity\nas Son of God.\nv. 23; cf. the description of angels as men in Acts 1:10;\n10:3, 30). The two men double Mark\u2019s solitary \u201cyoung man\u201d (16:5) and Mat-\nthew\u2019s singular \u201cangel\u201d (28:2, 5), thereby strengthening the credibility of their\n[v_Deu_19_15] witness (cf. Deut 19:15) but also forging a tight link to Luke 9:30\u201331 and its two\nmen (Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` and Elijah). Bypassing any words of assurance (such as those pro-\n[v_Mrk_16_6] vided in Mark 16:6; Matt 28:5), the men immediately commence the women\u2019s\nreeducation with a query that implies the need for corrected perception: \u201cWhy\nare you looking for one who is alive among the dead?\u201d (Luke 24:5b). God is,\nafter all, God of the living (20:38). Then follows a rekindling of forgotten or\nsuppressed memory: \u201cRemember the way he spoke to you when he was still in\nGalilee: \u2018The Son of Humanity must be handed over into the hands of sinful\nhumans, and crucified, and on the third day rise\u2019\u201d (24:6b\u20137). In a chapter that\nwith emphatic repetition interprets the events of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 passion and resurrection\nas fulfillment of scriptural prophecy and expectation (24:25\u201327, 44\u201346), the\nfirst note of fulfillment is struck with appeal to Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 own prophetic announce-\nment (\nv. 23)\nthe Eleven16 assembled\u2014and everyone else \u201cwith them,\u201d strong images of\ncommunal solidarity and cohesion (",
